&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Morales speaks in Mexico, where he seeks political asylum.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;With the protests continuing to rage on, violence began to erupt. A bounty was put on Morales’ head and armed intruders broke into his home in Cochabamba. Shortly after, an arsonist attack took place at his sister’s home. After several weeks of protests, the head of military suggested to Morales that he should resign.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After resigning, Morales fled Cochabamba for Mexico, where they immediately offered him political asylum.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just like that, Morales and the MAS were overthrown.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&quot;was-it-actually-a-coup&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#was-it-actually-a-coup&quot; aria-label=&quot;was it actually a coup permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Was it &lt;em&gt;actually&lt;/em&gt; a coup?&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is controversy whether if this ‘political crisis’ was either a coup d’état or a popular uprising. I personally think that the two are not mutually exclusive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let’s take a look at the definition of both terms:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;coup&lt;/strong&gt; or &lt;strong&gt;coup d’état&lt;/strong&gt; is the removal of an existing government from power, usually through violent means.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A &lt;strong&gt;popular uprising&lt;/strong&gt; is a popular revolt that attempts to overthrow a government or its policies.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I think it’s pretty easy to say that this political crisis can be classified as both a coup, and a popular uprising. It’s pretty clear that the people were suspicious of a dictatorship and they were compelled to do something to overthrow the government — but the amount of violence that ensued makes it hard to not consider it a coup. In retrospect, seeing how convincingly the MAS won the presidential election only a year after it was violently overthrown makes it even easier to argue that this event was in fact, a coup.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&quot;us-involvement-in-the-coup&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#us-involvement-in-the-coup&quot; aria-label=&quot;us involvement in the coup permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;U.S involvement in the coup&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Governments that don’t align with the U.S’ interests tend to get overthrown, especially in Latin America. Here’s a wikipedia article titled ”&lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_involvement_in_regime_change_in_Latin_America&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;United States involvement in regime change in Latin America&lt;/a&gt;“.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Overthrowing governments in Latin America was at its peak for the United States during the Cold War to contain geopolitical expansion of the Soviet Union. Overthrowing these governments was aligned with the famous &lt;a href=&quot;https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Truman_Doctrine&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener noreferrer&quot;&gt;Truman Doctrine&lt;/a&gt;. Many Latin American countries had their democratically elected presidents overthrown by the U.S government, purely for the reason that their political ideology was not aligned with the U.S’. These coups usually led to far-right military dictatorships — some examples of where this happened include Argentina, Uruguay, and of course, Bolivia.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now hold on a second, the Cold War ended decades ago…&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Why is the U.S interested in overthrowing Bolivia’s government again?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/blockquote&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Lithium. “The new oil”. The bipolar disorder-treating, battery-powering element.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&quot;lets-talk-about-lithium&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#lets-talk-about-lithium&quot; aria-label=&quot;lets talk about lithium permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Let’s talk about lithium&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As the world makes a shift towards clean energy, lithium is becoming a more and more valuable natural resource. Lithium is one of the key resources in batteries. To make electric vehicle batteries, and batteries that store energy generated by solar panels and wind turbines, you’re going to need lithium.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bolivia has a shit ton of lithium. They are home to the world’s largest salt flat, which alone contains 23 million tons of lithium — and that’s one of their many salt flats. For comparison, Australia, who is currently the world’s leader in production of lithium, only has 6.9 million tons.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tesla, as the world leader in electric vehicle development, has a large interest in obtaining lithium for cheaper since it’s such a key resource for their products. Elon Musk, Tesla’s CEO, has publicly supported the coup in Bolivia and is most likely the reason why the U.S overthrew the Bolivian government in the first place. He tweeted that “We will coup whoever we want” and that they should just “Deal with it”.&lt;/p&gt;
