&lt;p&gt;During this interim period, the already existing polarization between indigenous and non-indigenous people were escalated. Áñez’s presidency contributed a lot to this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Despite Bolivia’s population being 41% indigenous, Áñez’s cabinet initially had absolutely zero indigenous representation&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Áñez had previously called the Aymara people’s New Year celebration as “satanic”, saying that “nobody can replace God”, and some other racist tweets&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There were also massacres following violent protests in Senkata and Sacaba, areas with high indigenous populations. There was controversy about Áñez’s government when they granted immunity to military and police forces for their crimes while repressing these protestors — the repression led to 6 dead and 115 wounded.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&quot;2020-bolivian-general-election&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#2020-bolivian-general-election&quot; aria-label=&quot;2020 bolivian general election permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;2020 Bolivian general election&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Jeanine Áñez had decided to not run for the presidency in the 2020 election, since she didn’t want to risk splitting the vote between conservative candidates. The MAS appointed Luis Arce, former Minister of Finance under Morales, as their candidate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The 2020 election was a landslide for the MAS for the presidency, the senate, and the chamber:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Luis Arce won 55.10% of the popular vote, with the runner-up having only 28.83%&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The MAS won 21/36 seats in the senate, a majority&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;The MAS won 75/130 seats in the chamber, a majority&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Not only was this a massive win for the MAS, but also for democracy as a whole.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&quot;what-now&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#what-now&quot; aria-label=&quot;what now permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;What now?&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Arce has a ton of work to do. Bolivia has been one of hardest hit countries by the Coronavirus disease, and the country is in an economic crisis. There is hope that he will do well to rebuild the economy due to his expertise in economics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are many questions for how the MAS will handle things in the future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;What role will Morales have in Arce’s administration? How will they rebuild their economy? How will they go about handling the gold mine of lithium that they’re sitting on?&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;But for now, they should congratulate themselves on a purely democractic landslide victory.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;h4 id=&quot;final-thoughts&quot; style=&quot;position:relative;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;#final-thoughts&quot; aria-label=&quot;final thoughts permalink&quot; class=&quot;anchor before&quot;&gt;&lt;svg aria-hidden=&quot;true&quot; focusable=&quot;false&quot; height=&quot;16&quot; version=&quot;1.1&quot; viewBox=&quot;0 0 16 16&quot; width=&quot;16&quot;&gt;&lt;path fill-rule=&quot;evenodd&quot; d=&quot;M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z&quot;&gt;&lt;/path&gt;&lt;/svg&gt;&lt;/a&gt;Final thoughts&lt;/h4&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bolivia’s win and the MAS’ win is a big move for moderate socialism in Latin America. Whatever your views on socialism are, you have to agree that democracy being practiced to its core is a great thing to see — and that they have the right to run their country how their people have decided they want it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I can’t help myself but cheer for the underdog — it’s exciting to see the U.S’ attempts at tapping Bolivia’s lithium reserves completely fail. We’re not sure if lithium will become the next oil. But if it does, we will know for a fact that the lithium capital of the world won’t give in so easily to the U.S.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Congratulations to Luis Arce, the MAS, and Bolivia!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;(and to me for finally finishing this article)&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item></channel></rss>